The firm also announced a $50 price cut for its 32 GB Wii U console in North America and Europe from $349 to $299 - around £193 - following disappointing sales of the console.

Nintendo sold just 3.6 million Wii U units sold since launch to June 30 compared to 9.3 million units of its predecessor, the Wii.

However, the eight month-old Wii U faces stiff competition from Sony Corp's PlayStation 4, priced at £257 ($399) and Microsoft Corp's Xbox One, priced at £322 ($499) which will hit store shelves in November.

